Suppose node j is the score manager of node i, it stores a pair Ã°vi; iÃž for node i, where vi is the global reputation of node i. Node j hashes the reputation value vi using a LPH function to a hash value HÃ°viÃž and inserts the triplet Ã°vi; i; jÃž to the successor node of HÃ°viÃž. The triplets are stored in the ascending order of their reputation values in the DHT hash space due to the property of LPH. Assume node x is the successor node of the maximum hash value and it stores k triplets with highest reputation values. If k is less than m, node x sends a message to its predecessor node y to find the next m Ã€ k highest reputation triplets. This process repeats recursively until the m highest reputation triplets are found.
Basically, distributed reputation ranking requires two different hash overlays. One assigns peers to their score managers and another ranks the peers by their global reputation scores. Fig. 4 presents a 5-node PowerTrust system built on top of a Chord with 4-bit circular hash space. Node N15 is the score manager of node N2 whose global reputation is 0.2. Node N15 hashes the reputation value 0.2 using a simple LPH function HÃ°xÃž Â¼ 32x. The resulting hash value is 6.4. Node N15 sends out Sort Requestfkey Â¼ 6:4; Ã°0:2; N2; N15Ãžg message, which is routed to node N8. Node N8 stores the triplet (0.2, N2, N15), since it is the successor node of hash value 6.4. For simplicity, we illustrate below how to find the highest reputation node with m Â¼ 1.
